INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0fe0b2ce-ce5d-4a1a-81b1-d8c6a9837105',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Cypress Testing Pyramid — What Belongs at Each Level$escape$,
  $escape$Cypress collapses the traditional pyramid: you write component tests AND E2E tests in the same tool, same syntax. That's powerful, but it makes the boundary between levels easy to blur.

Unit level → use `cy.mount()` (Cypress Component Testing). Mount a single component, stub props and events, assert rendered output. No routing, no network. Fast, isolated. Best for logic-heavy components: form validation, conditional rendering, custom hooks via wrapper components.

Integration level → still `cy.mount()`, but compose multiple components together. Let them communicate naturally. Use `cy.intercept()` to stub API calls at the boundary. Assert that parent-child wiring works without spinning up a full browser session.

E2E level → full `cy.visit()` flows. Reserve these for critical user journeys: sign-up, checkout, auth redirect. Don't assert UI copy here — assert state changes, URL transitions, and API calls via `cy.intercept().as()` + `cy.wait('@alias')`. E2E is expensive; keep it thin.

The practical ratio for a Cypress-only project: ~60% component tests, ~25% integration mounts, ~15% E2E flows.$escape$,
  $escape$// Component test (unit level) — isolated, no network
cy.mount(<PriceTag amount={99.99} currency="USD" />);
cy.get('[data-testid="price"]').should('have.text', '$99.99');

// Integration mount — stub the API boundary
cy.intercept('POST', '/api/cart', { statusCode: 200, body: { id: 'abc' } }).as('addToCart');
cy.mount(<ProductCard productId="123" />);
cy.get('[data-testid="add-btn"]').click();
cy.wait('@addToCart').its('request.body').should('include', { productId: '123' });

// E2E — critical journey only
cy.visit('/checkout');
cy.intercept('POST', '/api/orders').as('placeOrder');
cy.get('#submit-order').click();
cy.wait('@placeOrder').its('response.statusCode').should('eq', 201);
cy.url().should('include', '/order-confirmation');$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
