INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '59e966ae-7119-4915-aa04-685f085e495b',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Cypress — Test Behaviour Not Implementation with Accessible Queries$escape$,
  $escape$Most Cypress tests break not because the feature broke, but because a class name changed. That's a test smell. Instead of `cy.get('.btn-primary')` or `cy.get('#submit-form')`, reach for queries that mirror how a real user interacts with the DOM — by role, label, and text.

Cypress ships with `cy.findByRole()`, `cy.findByLabelText()`, and `cy.findByText()` via the `@testing-library/cypress` plugin. These bind to semantic meaning, not implementation details. A button is still a button whether it has class `btn-v2` or `btn-v3`.

`cy.findByRole('button', { name: /submit/i })` finds the submit button by its accessible name — the same way a screen reader would. `cy.findByLabelText('Email')` targets an input through its `<label>` association, not an arbitrary `id`.

This approach also enforces accessibility by design — if your query can't find the element, neither can assistive technology. When a refactor renames CSS classes, these tests survive. When markup becomes inaccessible, they fail — exactly when they should.$escape$,
  $escape$// Install: npm install --save-dev @testing-library/cypress
// In cypress/support/commands.ts:
import '@testing-library/cypress/add-commands';

// Bad — brittle, tied to implementation
cy.get('.login-form .btn-primary').click();

// Good — semantic, behaviour-driven
cy.findByLabelText('Email').type('dev@byteai.io');
cy.findByLabelText('Password').type('hunter2');
cy.findByRole('button', { name: /sign in/i }).click();

// Assert on visible outcome, not DOM structure
cy.findByText('Welcome back').should('be.visible');$escape$,
