INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c0744205-4fcc-4305-a04d-c8b2d4d0c8e2',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Cypress Component Testing — Mount, Interact, Assert Without a Browser$escape$,
  $escape$Cypress Component Testing lets you mount a single component in isolation using `cy.mount()`, bypassing the need for a full application or dev server route. Unlike E2E tests, the component renders directly in Cypress's browser sandbox, giving you sub-second feedback loops.

Mount your component with props, then drive it exactly as a user would — `cy.get()`, `cy.click()`, `cy.type()`. Cypress's command queue is async but reads synchronously, so no `await` is needed. Assertions use `.should()` chained off queries, and Cypress retries them automatically until the timeout.

For a button that toggles a label, mount it, click it, then assert the DOM reflects the new state. Use `cy.contains()` when asserting on visible text rather than reaching into implementation details like state variables. Stub props or callbacks with `cy.stub()` to verify emission of events without wiring up a parent.

Coverage: Cypress instruments component tests with the same Istanbul-based coverage used in E2E, so you get unified reports with no extra tooling.$escape$,
  $escape$import { mount } from 'cypress/react';
import ToggleButton from './ToggleButton';

describe('ToggleButton', () => {
  it('flips label on click', () => {
    const onToggle = cy.stub().as('toggleHandler');

    mount(<ToggleButton onToggle={onToggle} />);

    cy.contains('OFF').click();
    cy.contains('ON').should('be.visible');
    cy.get('@toggleHandler').should('have.been.calledOnceWith', true);
  });
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
