INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '44f0c5c2-133b-43b8-aad1-a506c966e395',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Cypress Async Testing — cy.intercept, findBy, and Clock Control Done Right$escape$,
  $escape$Cypress commands are already async and chainable — but async testing breaks down when you fight the framework instead of working with it.

Avoid `cy.wait(2000)` for network responses. Use `cy.intercept()` with an alias and `cy.wait('@alias')` instead — this gates on the actual request completing, not an arbitrary timeout.

For DOM assertions, Cypress automatically retries `.should()` and chained queries up to `defaultCommandTimeout` (4s by default). You rarely need `cy.findByText()` from Testing Library unless your team is standardizing on those selectors — native `cy.contains()` and `cy.get()` already retry.

Fake timers shine when testing debounced inputs or polling intervals. Call `cy.clock()` before mounting, then `cy.tick(ms)` to advance time synchronously. Restore with `cy.clock().then(c => c.restore())` or let `afterEach` handle it.

Promise-based utilities returned from `cy.wrap(promise)` integrate cleanly — Cypress queues them into its command chain, so assertions after `cy.wrap()` wait for resolution automatically.$escape$,
  $escape$// Intercept + alias — no arbitrary waits
cy.intercept('POST', '/api/search').as('search');
cy.get('[data-cy=search-input]').type('cypress');
cy.wait('@search').its('response.statusCode').should('eq', 200);

// Fake timers for debounced input (300ms debounce)
cy.clock();
cy.get('[data-cy=search-input]').type('async');
cy.tick(300);
cy.get('[data-cy=results]').should('have.length.greaterThan', 0);

// Wrap a promise into the Cypress chain
const fetchToken = () => Promise.resolve('tok_abc123');
cy.wrap(fetchToken()).then((token) => {
  cy.request({ url: '/api/me', headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${token}` } })
    .its('status').should('eq', 200);
});$escape$,
