INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '5a65df53-e1b2-4cb0-906d-9d92b27a247a',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Cypress Accessibility Testing — Automating a11y Checks with axe-core$escape$,
  $escape$Cypress integrates with axe-core via `cypress-axe`, giving you automated WCAG compliance checks directly inside your test suite. After installing `cypress-axe` and `axe-core`, inject the axe runtime with `cy.injectAxe()` after your page loads, then call `cy.checkA11y()` to audit the entire DOM — or scope it to a selector like `cy.checkA11y('#modal')` to isolate a component.

By default, `checkA11y()` fails the test on any axe violation. You can tighten or relax this with the `runOnly` option to target specific WCAG rules, or pass an `includedImpacts` filter to only fail on `critical` and `serious` issues — useful for gradual a11y adoption without blocking CI on minor infractions.

Combine with `cy.get().focus()` or `.tab()` (via `cypress-plugin-tab`) to test keyboard navigation flows. Log violations to the Cypress command log using a custom `violationCallback` so failures surface with rule IDs, impact level, and the offending DOM node — making triage fast without leaving Cypress.$escape$,
  $escape$// cypress/support/commands.ts
import 'cypress-axe';

// In your spec file:
beforeEach(() => {
  cy.visit('/dashboard');
  cy.injectAxe();
});

it('has no critical a11y violations', () => {
  cy.checkA11y(
    '#main-content',
    {
      runOnly: { type: 'tag', values: ['wcag2a', 'wcag2aa'] },
      includedImpacts: ['critical', 'serious'],
    },
    (violations) => {
      violations.forEach((v) =>
        cy.log(`[${v.impact}] ${v.id}: ${v.nodes[0].html}`)
      );
    }
  );
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
