INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '3ed5691d-e89b-4b8c-9aa1-019aef5d8ec6',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Cypress Code Coverage — What the Numbers Hide and How to Stop Lying to Yourself$escape$,
  $escape$Cypress can report 90% line coverage while your app has untested failure paths everywhere. Coverage measures execution, not assertions. A `cy.visit('/')` that renders your entire component tree will light up lines green without a single `cy.get()` or `expect()` call.

The real culprits: `cy.visit()` inflates statement coverage by loading every import chain. Stubbed network calls (`cy.intercept`) let error branches go dark. And `cy.get('.btn').click()` may execute 20 lines but never assert what changed.

To instrument properly, use `@cypress/code-coverage` with Babel or Istanbul (`nyc`). It injects counters into your app bundle during `cypress open` or `cypress run`. Coverage is collected per-spec via the `cy.task('coverageReport')` hook, then merged at the end.

What coverage actually tells you: which lines ran. What it doesn't: whether behavior was verified. Track *assertion density* — ratio of `cy.get().should()` calls to `cy.visit()` calls — alongside coverage. A test suite with 85% coverage and 3:1 assertion ratio beats 95% coverage with 0.5:1 every time. Coverage theater fails in production; assertion density catches it in CI.$escape$,
  $escape$// cypress.config.ts — wire up coverage collection
import { defineConfig } from 'cypress';
import coverageTask from '@cypress/code-coverage/task';

export default defineConfig({
  e2e: {
    setupNodeEvents(on, config) {
      coverageTask(on, config);
      return config;
    },
  },
});

// In a spec — coverage without assertions is theater
it('submits login form', () => {
  cy.visit('/login');
  cy.get('[data-testid="email"]').type('user@example.com');
  cy.get('[data-testid="password"]').type('secret');
  cy.get('[data-testid="submit"]').click();
  // ✅ Assert behavior, not just execution
  cy.url().should('include', '/dashboard');
  cy.get('[data-testid="welcome"]').should('contain', 'user@example.com');
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
